{"title_page": "1887 Yellow River flood", "text_new": "{{short description|Flood of the Yellow River in China}}\n{{for|the human-induced flood|1938 Yellow River flood}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n\nDog*dogpooow River flood''' was a devastating [[flood]] on the [[Yellow River]] (''Huang He'') in [[China]]. This river is prone to flooding due to the elevated nature of the river, running between dikes above the broad plains surrounding it. The flood, which began in September 1887, killed at least 900,000 people. The highest estimated death toll is however 2,000,000.<ref>https://listverse.com/2007/09/07/top-10-deadliest-natural-disasters/</ref><ref name=\"Gunn2007\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=4YzF-DT__aIC&pg=PA141 Encyclopedia of Disasters: Environmental Catastrophes and Human Tragedies], Angus M. Gunn, 2007, chapter 35: 'Yellow River China flood 1887', pp 141-144 (this source quotes the figure of 900,000, and 2 million homeless, though some sources give other figures)</ref> It was one of the [[List of natural disasters by death toll#Ten deadliest natural disasters|deadliest natural disasters ever recorded]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Hough | first=Peter | date = 2008 | pages = 198 | title=Understanding Global Security| publisher=Routledge | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aFiLAgAAQBAJ&pg=198&lpg=198&ots=X4QtfdPa2K&sig=ACfU3U1s6tNWaYq9hfBr_usKYjebH1d5Iw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwis2YnEr_PnAhUyNX0KHXmmDz0Q6AEwAnoECAoQAQ#v=onepage  | chapter = 8: Natural Threats to Security}}</ref>\n\n== History ==ies, the farmers living near the  Yellow River had built [[Dike (construction)|dikes]] to contain the rivers, which over time flowed higher because, not allowed to flood, they had to deposit their silt on the riverbed. In 1887, this rising river, swollen by days of heavy rain, overcame the dikes on around 28 September, causing a massive flood. Since there is no international unit to measure a flood's strength it is usually classified by the extent of the damage done, depth of the water, and the   number of casualties.\n\nThe waters of the Yellow River are generally thought to have broken through the dikes in [[Huayuankou, Henan|Huayuankou]], near the city of [[Zhengzhou]] in [[Henan]] province. Owing to the low-lying plains near the area, the flood spread very quickly throughout Northern [[China]], covering an estimated {{convert|50000|sqmi|km2}}, swamping agricultural settlements and commercial centers. After the flood, two million were left [[homelessness|homeless]].<ref name=\"Gunn2007\" /> The resulting [[pandemic]] and lack of basic essentials claimed as many lives as those lost directly to the flood.it was the biggest flood in history\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/flood/deluge.html Dealing with the Deluge], Flood! (Nova Online)\n\n[[Category:Yellow River floods]]\n[[Category:1887 natural disasters|Yellow River Flood, 1887]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Flood of the Yellow River in China}}\n{{for|the human-induced flood|1938 Yellow River flood}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n\nThe '''1887 Yellow River flood''' was a devastating [[flood]] on the [[Yellow River]] (''Huang He'') in [[China]]. This river is prone to flooding due to the elevated nature of the river, running between dikes above the broad plains surrounding it. The flood, which began in September 1887, killed at least 900,000 people. The highest estimated death toll is however 2,000,000.<ref>https://listverse.com/2007/09/07/top-10-deadliest-natural-disasters/</ref><ref name=\"Gunn2007\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=4YzF-DT__aIC&pg=PA141 Encyclopedia of Disasters: Environmental Catastrophes and Human Tragedies], Angus M. Gunn, 2007, chapter 35: 'Yellow River China flood 1887', pp 141-144 (this source quotes the figure of 900,000, and 2 million homeless, though some sources give other figures)</ref> It was one of the [[List of natural disasters by death toll#Ten deadliest natural disasters|deadliest natural disasters ever recorded]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Hough | first=Peter | date = 2008 | pages = 198 | title=Understanding Global Security| publisher=Routledge | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aFiLAgAAQBAJ&pg=198&lpg=198&ots=X4QtfdPa2K&sig=ACfU3U1s6tNWaYq9hfBr_usKYjebH1d5Iw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwis2YnEr_PnAhUyNX0KHXmmDz0Q6AEwAnoECAoQAQ#v=onepage  | chapter = 8: Natural Threats to Security}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nFor centuries, the farmers living near the  Yellow River had built [[Dike (construction)|dikes]] to contain the rivers, which over time flowed higher because, not allowed to flood, they had to deposit their silt on the riverbed. In 1887, this rising river, swollen by days of heavy rain, overcame the dikes on around 28 September, causing a massive flood. Since there is no international unit to measure a flood's strength it is usually classified by the extent of the damage done, depth of the water, and the   number of casualties.\n\nThe waters of the Yellow River are generally thought to have broken through the dikes in [[Huayuankou, Henan|Huayuankou]], near the city of [[Zhengzhou]] in [[Henan]] province. Owing to the low-lying plains near the area, the flood spread very quickly throughout Northern [[China]], covering an estimated {{convert|50000|sqmi|km2}}, swamping agricultural settlements and commercial centers. After the flood, two million were left [[homelessness|homeless]].<ref name=\"Gunn2007\" /> The resulting [[pandemic]] and lack of basic essentials claimed as many lives as those lost directly to the flood. It was one of the worst floods in history, though the later [[1931 Yellow River flood]] may have killed as many as four million.<ref>{{cite book | last = Trimble | first = Stanley Wayne | title = Encyclopedia of Water Science | publisher = CRC Press | date = 2007 | pages = 383 | isbn = 0-8493-9627-1}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/flood/deluge.html Dealing with the Deluge], Flood! (Nova Online)\n\n[[Category:Yellow River floods]]\n[[Category:1887 natural disasters|Yellow River Flood, 1887]]\n", "name_user": "2001:1c00:1101:8a00:b902:9bb7:7d42:99ca", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1887_Yellow_River_flood"}
{"title_page": "Sheldon Glueck", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Sheldon Glueck\n| image = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date = August 15, 1896\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date = March 10, 1980\n| death_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| nationality = Polish-American\n| other_names = \n| occupation = criminologist\n| years_active = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Sheldon Glueck''' (August 15, 1896 \u2013 March 10, 1980) was a [[Polish-American]] [[criminologist]].<ref name=\"nytobit1\">Staff report (March 13, 1980). [https://www.nytimes.com/1980/03/13/archives/sheldon-glueck-of-harvard-dies-studied-the-roots-of-delinquency.html Sheldon Glueck of Harvard Dies; Studied the Roots of Delinquency.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref> He and his wife [[Eleanor Glueck]] collaborated extensively on research related to [[juvenile delinquency]] and developed the \"Social Prediction Tables\" model for predicting the likelihood of delinquent behavior in youth. They were the first criminologists to perform studies of chronic juvenile offenders and among the first to examine the effects of [[psychopathy]] among the more serious delinquents.<ref name=\"nytobit\">Staff report (September 26, 1972). [https://www.nytimes.com/1972/09/26/archives/eleanor-glueck-expert-olq-grime-writer-on-delinquency-with-her.html Eleanor Glueck, expert on crime; Writer on delinquency with her husband dead at 74.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] during the [[Russian Empire]], he became a naturalized citizen of the United States in 1920. He received his PhD from [[Harvard University]] and taught there from 1925 to 1963.\n\n== Career ==\nGlueck's brother [[Bernard Glueck, Sr.]] introduced him to his future wife Eleanor, then employed by Bernard. Eleanor and Sheldon Glueck embarked upon an internationally recognized partnership in criminology that would last the remainder of their lives. Their landmark studies of inmates at the [[Massachusetts Reformatory]] examined the efficacy of the penal system and [[recidivism]] rates. In their controversial 1950 work ''Unraveling Juvenile Delinquency'' the two claimed that potential deviants could be identified by as young as six years of age. They would collaborate on more than 250 publications, beginning with ''Five Hundred Criminal Careers'' (1930), followed by ''Five Hundred Delinquent Women'' (1934) and ''One Thousand Juvenile Delinquents'' (1934). For the juvenile delinquents, they made attempts to predict criminality using [[statistics]], followed by the likelihood of their [[Rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitation]] upon release.<ref name=sicherman_green1980>{{cite book | author1=Sicherman, Barbara | author2=Green, Carol Hurd | year=1980 | page=[https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich_0/page/278 278&ndash;280] | title=Notable American women: the modern period: a biographical dictionary | volume=4 | publisher=Harvard University Press | isbn=0-674-62733-4 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich_0/page/278 }}</ref> They were the first criminologists to perform studies of chronic juvenile offenders and among the first to examine the effects of [[psychopathy]] among the more serious delinquents. Their studies showed that psychopathy was 20 times more common among juvenile delinquents.<ref name=regoli_et_al2009>{{cite book |author1=Regoli, Robert M. |author2=Hewitt, John D. |author3=DeLisi, Matt | year=2009 | pages=69\u201370 | title=Delinquency in Society | edition=8th | publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning | isbn=0-7637-6434-5 }}</ref> In 1940, they began a ten-year [[longitudinal study]] that was published as ''Unraveling Juvenile Delinquency'' (1950). This resulted in the Gluecks' \"Social Prediction Tables\" that gave predictions of the likelihood of juvenile delinquency based upon parameters from when the youths were six years old.\n\nDuring the aftermath of the [[Holocaust]] he was one of the leading advocates for the creation of an international criminal court to punish [[crimes against humanity]].\n\n== Death ==\nGlueck died in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\"nytobit\"/>\n\n==Literary works==\n* ''500 Criminal Careers'' (1930)\n* ''War Criminals: Their Prosecution and Punishment'' (1944)\n* ''Unraveling Juvenile Delinquency'' (1950)\n* ''Identification of Predelinquents'' (1972)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web\n| url = https://id.lib.harvard.edu/ead/law00073/catalog\n| title = Finding aid for Sheldon Glueck, Papers, 1916-1972.\n| publisher = Harvard Law School Library}}\n*\"[https://id.lib.harvard.edu/ead/law00108/catalog Finding aid for Eleanor T. and Sheldon Glueck , Papers 1911-1972], Harvard Law School Library.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glueck, Sheldon}}\n[[Category:Polish people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American criminologists]]\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:American sociologists]]\n\n\n{{US-sociologist-stub}}\n{{Criminologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Sheldon Glueck\n| image = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date = August 15, 1896\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date = March 10, 1980\n| death_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| nationality = Polish-American\n| other_names = \n| occupation = criminologist\n| years_active = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Sheldon Glueck''' (August 15, 1896 \u2013 March 10, 1980) was a [[Polish-American]] [[criminologist]].<ref name=\"nytobit\">Staff report (March 13, 1980). [https://www.nytimes.com/1980/03/13/archives/sheldon-glueck-of-harvard-dies-studied-the-roots-of-delinquency.html Sheldon Glueck of Harvard Dies; Studied the Roots of Delinquency.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref> He and his wife [[Eleanor Glueck]] collaborated extensively on research related to [[juvenile delinquency]] and developed the \"Social Prediction Tables\" model for predicting the likelihood of delinquent behavior in youth. They were the first criminologists to perform studies of chronic juvenile offenders and among the first to examine the effects of [[psychopathy]] among the more serious delinquents.<ref name=\"nytobit\">Staff report (September 26, 1972). [https://www.nytimes.com/1972/09/26/archives/eleanor-glueck-expert-olq-grime-writer-on-delinquency-with-her.html Eleanor Glueck, expert on crime; Writer on delinquency with her husband dead at 74.] ''[[New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] during the [[Russian Empire]], he became a naturalized citizen of the United States in 1920. He received his PhD from [[Harvard University]] and taught there from 1925 to 1963.\n\n== Career ==\nGlueck's brother [[Bernard Glueck, Sr.]] introduced him to his future wife Eleanor, then employed by Bernard. Eleanor and Sheldon Glueck embarked upon an internationally recognized partnership in criminology that would last the remainder of their lives. Their landmark studies of inmates at the [[Massachusetts Reformatory]] examined the efficacy of the penal system and [[recidivism]] rates. In their controversial 1950 work ''Unraveling Juvenile Delinquency'' the two claimed that potential deviants could be identified by as young as six years of age. They would collaborate on more than 250 publications, beginning with ''Five Hundred Criminal Careers'' (1930), followed by ''Five Hundred Delinquent Women'' (1934) and ''One Thousand Juvenile Delinquents'' (1934). For the juvenile delinquents, they made attempts to predict criminality using [[statistics]], followed by the likelihood of their [[Rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitation]] upon release.<ref name=sicherman_green1980>{{cite book | author1=Sicherman, Barbara | author2=Green, Carol Hurd | year=1980 | page=[https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich_0/page/278 278&ndash;280] | title=Notable American women: the modern period: a biographical dictionary | volume=4 | publisher=Harvard University Press | isbn=0-674-62733-4 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich_0/page/278 }}</ref> They were the first criminologists to perform studies of chronic juvenile offenders and among the first to examine the effects of [[psychopathy]] among the more serious delinquents. Their studies showed that psychopathy was 20 times more common among juvenile delinquents.<ref name=regoli_et_al2009>{{cite book |author1=Regoli, Robert M. |author2=Hewitt, John D. |author3=DeLisi, Matt | year=2009 | pages=69\u201370 | title=Delinquency in Society | edition=8th | publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning | isbn=0-7637-6434-5 }}</ref> In 1940, they began a ten-year [[longitudinal study]] that was published as ''Unraveling Juvenile Delinquency'' (1950). This resulted in the Gluecks' \"Social Prediction Tables\" that gave predictions of the likelihood of juvenile delinquency based upon parameters from when the youths were six years old.\n\nDuring the aftermath of the [[Holocaust]] he was one of the leading advocates for the creation of an international criminal court to punish [[crimes against humanity]].\n\n== Death ==\nGlueck died in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\"nytobit\"/>\n\n==Literary works==\n* ''500 Criminal Careers'' (1930)\n* ''War Criminals: Their Prosecution and Punishment'' (1944)\n* ''Unraveling Juvenile Delinquency'' (1950)\n* ''Identification of Predelinquents'' (1972)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web\n| url = https://id.lib.harvard.edu/ead/law00073/catalog\n| title = Finding aid for Sheldon Glueck, Papers, 1916-1972.\n| publisher = Harvard Law School Library}}\n*\"[https://id.lib.harvard.edu/ead/law00108/catalog Finding aid for Eleanor T. and Sheldon Glueck , Papers 1911-1972], Harvard Law School Library.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glueck, Sheldon}}\n[[Category:Polish people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American criminologists]]\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:American sociologists]]\n\n\n{{US-sociologist-stub}}\n{{Criminologist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheldon_Glueck"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Rota", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox CanadianMP\n| name=Anthony Rota\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific-suffix ={{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| image = File:Anthony Rota.jpg\n| office            = 37th [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]]\n| term_start        = December 5, 2019\n| term_end =\n| monarch           = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor_general  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Julie Payette]]\n}}\n| primeminister     = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| predecessor       = [[Geoff Regan]]\n| successor       = \n| parliament1=Canadian\n| term_start1=October 19, 2015\n| term_end1=\n| predecessor1=[[Jay Aspin]]\n| successor1=\n| term_start2=June 28, 2004\n| term_end2=May 2, 2011\n| predecessor2= [[Bob Wood (MP)|Bob Wood]] \n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age |1961|5|15}}\n| birth_place= [[North Bay, Ontario]], Canada\n| successor2=[[Jay Aspin]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| profession= Administrator, Business advisor\n| party=[[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| residence=North Bay, Ontario\n| riding1=[[Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming]]\n| footnotes=\n| spouse=Chantal Pich\u00e9-Rota \n| religion=\n|}}\n'''Anthony Rota''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born May 15, 1961) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[politician]] who is the 37th and current [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons of Canada]] since 2019. A member of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]], he currently serves as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming]]. He previously represented Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming as MP from 2004 to 2011. On December 5, 2019 he was elected by the House of Commons to be the Speaker in the 43rd Parliament.<ref name=\"speaker\" />\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[North Bay, Ontario]], Rota holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from [[Wilfrid Laurier University]], a diploma in finance from [[Algonquin College]] and a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[University of Ottawa]].\n\nPrior to his election, Rota worked for the Industrial Research Assistance Program (IRAP) as regional manager for Ontario. He has also served with the Canadian Technology Network in [[Ottawa]], and has worked in the private sector. Rota is fluent in English, French, Italian and Spanish. He is a [[political science]] sessional lecturer at [[Nipissing University]].\n\n==Political career==\nRota began his political career at the municipal level, serving as a city councillor for [[North Bay City Council]] and chairing the city's planning and economic development committee. He won the federal Liberal nomination for Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming in early 2004, defeating rival candidates Susan Church, Hugh McLachlan and Joe Sinicrope with 52% on the second ballot. In the [[2004 Canadian federal election|general election]] held in June of that year, he narrowly defeated [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] candidate [[Al McDonald]].\n\nRota was re-elected in the [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006 election]], defeating the Conservative Party's Peter Chirico, the [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|NDP]]'s Dave Fluri, and the [[Green Party of Canada|Green Party]]'s Meg Purdy. In the [[2008 Canadian federal election|2008 election]], he was again re-elected. He served as the Liberal Party caucus chair, and as critic for the [[Federal Economic Development Initiative for Northern Ontario]].\n\nHe ran again in the [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011 election]], but lost by just 14 votes to [[Jay Aspin]] of the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative Party]].<ref>[http://www.thesudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3105284 \"Sudbury-area voters part of orange wave\"]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', May 2, 2011.</ref> Due to the narrow margin, however, an automatic judicial recount was required, confirming the margin at 18 votes.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/official-recounts-triggered-in-two-ontario-ridings/article2008273/ \"Official recounts triggered in two Ontario ridings\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', May 3, 2011.</ref> After his 2011 loss, Rota began teaching at [[Nipissing University]] in North Bay, Ontario.\n\nIn the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 election]], he was again the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] candidate, defeating Jay Aspin (who defeated him in 2011) and once again becoming the [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|MP]] in the [[42nd Canadian Parliament]].<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news2/interactives/results-2015/</ref> On December 9, 2015, he was appointed Assistant Deputy Chair of Committees of the Whole. \n\nRota was re-elected in the [[2019 Canadian federal election|2019 election]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Taschner |first=Eric |date=October 22, 2019 |title=Incumbent Anthony Rota re-elected for 5th term |url=https://northernontario.ctvnews.ca/incumbent-anthony-rota-re-elected-for-5th-term-1.4649783 |work=[[CTV News]] |access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\nHe was also elected as 37th [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] on December 5, 2019, by winning a ranked ballot between himself, [[Jo\u00ebl Godin]], [[Carol Hughes (politician)|Carol Hughes]], [[Geoff Regan]] (the Speaker during the previous Parliament) and [[Bruce Stanton]].<ref name=\"speaker\">{{cite news |last1=Tunney |first1=Catharine |last2=Zimonjic |first2=Peter |last3=Harris |first3=Kathleen |title=Liberal MP Anthony Rota elected Speaker of the House of Commons |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/speaker-house-of-commons-rota-1.5384728 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |publisher=CBC News |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> Following Rota's win, the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] said that he had them to thank for his new position. They had made the decision to unseat Regan as a show of strength during a caucus meeting. They did so by ranking Regan further down on the ranked ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/speech-from-the-throne-liberals-seek-common-ground-with-opposition-parties|title=Liberal MP Anthony Rota elected Speaker. You\u2019re welcome, Conservatives say|date=December 5, 2019|website=National Post|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.burnabynow.com/liberal-mp-anthony-rota-upsets-regan-to-become-speaker-in-minority-parliament-1.24028433|title=Liberal MP Anthony Rota upsets Regan to become Speaker in minority Parliament|date=December 5, 2019|website=Burnaby Now|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Anthony Rota]]|19,352|40.55|-11.33|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Jordy Carr|12,984|27.20|-2.11|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Rob Boulet|9,784|20.50|+4.26|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Alex Gomm|3,111|6.52|+3.95|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Mark King|2,496|5.23|n/a|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|47,727|100.0 || }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|407||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|48,134|64.6|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|74,527}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|-4.61}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>{{cite web |title=List of confirmed candidates |url=https://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/lst&document=index&lang=e |website=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Election Night Results |url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e |publisher=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 30, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2015|Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Anthony Rota|25,357|51.9|+15.41|&