margin of win being less than 1/1000 of the total votes.}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2008|Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Anthony Rota|18,510|44.6|&ndash;0.1|$77,997}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Joe Sinicrope|13,432|32.3|&ndash;2.2|$81,801}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Dianna Allen|6,582|15.8|&ndash;1.5|$8,409}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Craig Bridges|2,808|6.8|+3.3|$10,803}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Canadian Action|Andrew Moulden|204|0.5|&ndash;| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|41,536| 100.0|$87,383}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|167| 0.4|0.0}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|41,703|~58.2|-9.4}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|+2.1}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2006|Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming|percent=yes|change=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Anthony Rota|21,393|44.7|+2.4}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Peter Chirico|16,511|34.5|&ndash;2.6}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Dave Fluri|8,268|17.3|+0.3}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Meg Purdy|1,698|3.5|+0.4}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes|47,870|100.0 }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|211| 0.4|-0.1}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|48,081|67.6|+5.2}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|+2.5}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2004|Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming|percent=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Anthony Rota|18,254|42.3}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|[[Al McDonald]]|16,001|37.1}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Dave Fluri|7,354|17.0}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Les Wilcox|1,329|3.1}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Canadian Action|Ross MacLean|204|0.5}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes|43,142| 100.0}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|222|0.5 }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|43,364|62.4}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://anthonyrota.ca View Anthony Rota]\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=9445}}\n\n{{Current Members of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n{{Speakers of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rota, Anthony}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n[[Category:North Bay, Ontario city councillors]]\n[[Category:Algonquin College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n[[Category:Wilfrid Laurier University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the House of Commons of Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox CanadianMP\n| name=Anthony Rota\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific-suffix ={{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| image = File:Anthony Rota.jpg\n| office            = 37th [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]]\n| term_start        = December 5, 2019\n| term_end =\n| monarch           = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor_general  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Julie Payette]]\n}}\n| primeminister     = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| predecessor       = [[Geoff Regan]]\n| successor       = \n| parliament1=Canadian\n| term_start1=October 19, 2015\n| term_end1=\n| predecessor1=[[Jay Aspin]]\n| successor1=\n| term_start2=June 28, 2004\n| term_end2=May 2, 2011\n| predecessor2= [[Bob Wood (MP)|Bob Wood]] \n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age |1961|5|15}}\n| birth_place= [[North Bay, Ontario]], Canada\n| successor2=[[Jay Aspin]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| profession= Administrator, Business advisor\n| party=[[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| residence=North Bay, Ontario\n| riding1=[[Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming]]\n| footnotes=\n| spouse=Chantal Pich\u00e9-Rota \n| religion=\n|}}\n'''Anthony Rota''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born May 15, 1961) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[politician]] who is the 37th and current [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons of Canada]] since 2019. A member of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]], he currently serves as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming]]. He previously represented Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming as MP from 2004 to 2011. On December 5, 2019 he was elected by the House of Commons to be the Speaker in the 43rd Parliament.<ref name=\"speaker\" />\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[North Bay, Ontario]], Rota holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from [[Wilfrid Laurier University]], a diploma in finance from [[Algonquin College]] and a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[University of Ottawa]].\n\nPrior to his election, Rota worked for the Industrial Research Assistance Program (IRAP) as regional manager for Ontario. He has also served with the Canadian Technology Network in [[Ottawa]], and has worked in the private sector. Rota is fluent in French, Spanish, Italian and English. He is a [[political science]] sessional lecturer at [[Nipissing University]].\n\n==Political career==\nRota began his political career at the municipal level, serving as a city councillor for [[North Bay City Council]] and chairing the city's planning and economic development committee. He won the federal Liberal nomination for Nipissing\u2014Timiskaming in early 2004, defeating rival candidates Susan Church, Hugh McLachlan and Joe Sinicrope with 52% on the second ballot. In the [[2004 Canadian federal election|general election]] held in June of that year, he narrowly defeated [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] candidate [[Al McDonald]].\n\nRota was re-elected in the [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006 election]], defeating the Conservative Party's Peter Chirico, the [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|NDP]]'s Dave Fluri, and the [[Green Party of Canada|Green Party]]'s Meg Purdy. In the [[2008 Canadian federal election|2008 election]], he was again re-elected. He served as the Liberal Party caucus chair, and as critic for the [[Federal Economic Development Initiative for Northern Ontario]].\n\nHe ran again in the [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011 election]], but lost by just 14 votes to [[Jay Aspin]] of the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative Party]].<ref>[http://www.thesudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3105284 \"Sudbury-area voters part of orange wave\"]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', May 2, 2011.</ref> Due to the narrow margin, however, an automatic judicial recount was required, confirming the margin at 18 votes.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/official-recounts-triggered-in-two-ontario-ridings/article2008273/ \"Official recounts triggered in two Ontario ridings\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', May 3, 2011.</ref> After his 2011 loss, Rota began teaching at [[Nipissing University]] in North Bay, Ontario.\n\nIn the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 election]], he was again the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] candidate, defeating Jay Aspin (who defeated him in 2011) and once again becoming the [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|MP]] in the [[42nd Canadian Parliament]].<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news2/interactives/results-2015/</ref> On December 9, 2015, he was appointed Assistant Deputy Chair of Committees of the Whole. \n\nRota was re-elected in the [[2019 Canadian federal election|2019 election]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Taschner |first=Eric |date=October 22, 2019 |title=Incumbent Anthony Rota re-elected for 5th term |url=https://northernontario.ctvnews.ca/incumbent-anthony-rota-re-elected-for-5th-term-1.4649783 |work=[[CTV News]] |access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\nHe was also elected as 37th [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] on December 5, 2019, by winning a ranked ballot between himself, [[Jo\u00ebl Godin]], [[Carol Hughes (politician)|Carol Hughes]], [[Geoff Regan]] (the Speaker during the previous Parliament) and [[Bruce Stanton]].<ref name=\"speaker\">{{cite news |last1=Tunney |first1=Catharine |last2=Zimonjic |first2=Peter |last3=Harris |first3=Kathleen |title=Liberal MP Anthony Rota elected Speaker of the House of Commons |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/speaker-house-of-commons-rota-1.5384728 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |publisher=CBC News |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> Following Rota's win, the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] said that he had them to thank for his new position. They had made the decision to unseat Regan as a show of strength during a caucus meeting. They did so by ranking Regan further down on the ranked ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/speech-from-the-throne-liberals-seek-common-ground-with-opposition-parties|title=Liberal MP Anthony Rota elected Speaker. You\u2019re welcome, Conservatives say|date=December 5, 2019|website=National Post|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.burnabynow.com/liberal-mp-anthony-rota-upsets-regan-to-become-speaker-in-minority-parliament-1.24028433|title=Liberal MP Anthony Rota upsets Regan to become Speaker in minority Parliament|date=December 5, 2019|website=Burnaby Now|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Anthony Rota]]|19,352|40.55|-11.33|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Jordy Carr|12,984|27.20|-2.11|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Rob Boulet|9,784|20.50|+4.26|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Alex Gomm|3,111|6.52|+3.95|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Mark King|2,496|5.23|n/a|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|47,727|100.0 || }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|407||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|48,134|64.6|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|74,527}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|-4.61}