n| 87%<ref name=\"PCJokerPCw\">{{cite magazine|last=Magenauer|first=Max|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=11814|title=Twilight \u2014 Games F\u00fcr Individualisten: Worms - Da ist der Wurm drin!|magazine=[[:de:PC Joker|PC Joker]]|issue=37|publisher=Joker-Verlag|date=December 1995|pages=78-79|lang=de}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:de:PC Player|PC Player]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 69/100<ref name=\"PCPlayerPCw\">{{cite magazine|last=Lenhardt|first=Heinrich|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=12228|title=Spiele-test - Worms|magazine=[[:de:PC Player|PC Player]]|issue=36|publisher=[[:de:Future plc|Future Verlag]]|date=December 1995|pages=108-109|lang=de}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[Play (UK magazine)|Play]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 92%<ref name=\"PlayPSw\">{{cite magazine|last=Ahmed|first=Asam|title=Reviews: Worms|magazine=[[Play (UK magazine)|Play]]|issue=1|publisher=[[Paragon Publishing]]|date=November 1995|pages=70-71}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 92%<ref name=\"POSMDw\">{{cite magazine|last=De Steene|first=Julien Van|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Player%20One/playerone_numero062/Player%20One%20062%20-%20Page%20099%20%281996-03%29.jpg|title=Tests - Megadrive: Worms|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=62|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=March 1996|page=99|lang=fr}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| 94%<ref name=\"POPSSSw\">{{cite magazine|last=Pottier|first=Christophe|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=32&num=1922&album=oui|title=Tests - PlayStation/Saturn: Worms|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=59|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=December 1995|pages=106\u2013108|lang=fr}}</ref>\n| 94%<ref name=\"POPSSSw\"/>\n| {{N/A}}\n| 92%<ref name=\"POSNESw\">{{cite magazine|last=De Steene|first=Julien Van|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Player%20One/playerone_numero069/PlayerOne_N069-Page%200112.jpg|title=Tests - Super Nintendo: Worms|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=69|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=November 1996|page=112|lang=fr}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''PlayStation Power''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 6/10<ref name=\"PSPowerPSw\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=Price Power - Worms|magazine=PlayStation Power|issue=1|publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]]|date=June 1996|page=60}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:de:Power Play (Zeitschrift)|Power Play]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| <small>(Single-player)</small> 74%<ref name=\"PPPCw\">{{cite magazine|last=Gliss|first=Sascha|url=https://archive.org/stream/powerplaymagazine-1995-12#page/n163/mode/2up|title=Test - Worms|magazine=[[:de:Power Play (Zeitschrift)|Power Play]]|issue=93|publisher=Future Verlag|date=December 1995|pages=164-165|lang=de}}</ref><br /><small>(Multiplayer)</small> 86%<ref name=\"PPPCw\"/>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:cs:Score (\u010dasopis)|Score]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 8/10<ref name=\"ScoPCw\">{{cite magazine|last=Stan\u011bk|first=Igor|url=https://www.oldgames.sk/en/mag/score-24/page/36/|title=Recenze - Worms|magazine=[[:cs:Score (\u010dasopis)|Score]]|issue=24|publisher=Omega Publishing Group|date=December 1995|page=36|lang=cs}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[Sega Power#Sega Power|Sega Power]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 78/100<ref name=\"SPowerSMDw\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=Reviews - Mega Drive - Worms|magazine=[[Sega Power#Sega Power|Sega Power]]|issue=76|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=March 1996|page=51}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 60/100<ref name=\"SPowerSSw\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=Reviews - Saturn - Worms|magazine=[[Sega Power#Sega Power|Sega Power]]|issue=76|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=March 1996|pages=48-50}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[Sega Pro]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 93%<ref name=\"SProSSw\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=Saturn - Review: Worms|magazine=[[Sega Pro]]|issue=53|publisher=[[Paragon Publishing]]|date=January 1996 |pages=54-55}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[Sega Saturn Magazine]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 90%<ref name=\"SSMukSSw\">{{cite magazine|last=Merrett|first=Steve|url=https://archive.org/details/Sega_Saturn_Magazine_Issue_03_1996-01_EMAP_Images_GB/page/n85/mode/2up|title=Review: Worms|magazine=[[Sega Saturn Magazine]]|issue=3|publisher=[[Ascential|EMAP]]|date=January 1996|pages=86-87}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30de\u30ac#SEGA SATURN MAGAZINE|Sega Saturn Magazine]] (JP)''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 6.33/10<ref name=\"SSMjpSSw\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:SSM_JP_19970321_1997-08.pdf&page=140|title=Sega Saturn Soft Review - WORMS|magazine=[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30de\u30ac#SEGA SATURN MAGAZINE|Sega Saturn Magazine]]|issue=44|publisher=[[SB Creative|SoftBank Creative]]|date=March 31, 1997|page=138|lang=ja}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:de:Total (Zeitschrift)|Total!]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 2-<ref name=\"T!GBw\">{{cite magazine|last=Koczy|first=Michael|title=Test - GB - Worms|magazine=[[:de:Total (Zeitschrift)|Total!]]|issue=34|publisher=X-Plain-Verlag|date=April 1996|page=59|lang=de}}</ref>\n| 2-<ref name=\"T!SNES\">{{cite magazine|last=H\u00e4ntsch|first=Marco|title=Test - SNES - Worms|magazine=[[:de:Total (Zeitschrift)|Total!]]|issue=42|publisher=X-Plain-Verlag|date=December 1996|pages=56-57|lang=de}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:fr:Nintendo Player|Ultra Player]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 5/6<ref name=\"UltraPlayerSNESw\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=Tests \u00e9clair - Super Nintendo - Worms|magazine=[[:fr:Nintendo Player|Ultra Player]]|issue=38|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=November-December 1996|page=102|lang=fr}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 70%<ref name=\"VGSMDw\">{{cite magazine|last=Schweinitz|first=Jan|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=13723|title=Mega Drive - Reviews: Kleinvieh - Worms|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=51|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=February 1996|page=90|lang=de}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| 85%<ref name=\"VGPSSSw\">{{cite magazine|last=Schweinitz|first=Jan|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=18691|title=Sony PlayStation/Sega Saturn - Reviews: Kraterparty - Worms|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=51|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=February 1996|pages=72-73|lang=de}}</ref>\n| 85%<ref name=\"VGPSSSw\"/>\n| {{N/A}}\n| 67%<ref name=\"VGSNESw>{{cite magazine|last=Schweinitz|first=Jan|url=https://www.ninretro.de/img/scans/snes/Worms_VG_3-97.jpg|title=Super Nintendo - Reviews: Wurmig - Worms|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=64|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=March 1997|page=101|lang=de}}</ref>\n| {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"VGJAGw\">{{cite magazine|last=Karels|first=Ralph|url=http://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=pic&id=4562&s=2|title=Special - Atari Jaguar - Komplett\u00fcbersicht Jaguar-Modul-Games - Worms|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=93|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=August 1999|page=56|lang=de|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804201520/http://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=pic&id=4562&s=2|archive-date=2018-08-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=10   | Awards\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" | Publication(s)\n! colspan=6   | Award(s)\n|-\n| colspan=4   | ''[[]]'' ()\n| colspan=6   | \n|}\n\n''Worms'' was a commercial success. By March 1996, its sales had reached almost 250,000 copies, following its release in November 1995.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|url=http://www.nuke.com/cgr/news/9603/worms.htm|title=Sales of Worms skyrockets|work=[[Computer Game Review]]|publisher=[[Ziff-Davis]]|date=1996|access-date=2020-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961018190644/http://www.nuke.com:80/cgr/news/9603/worms.htm|archive-date=1996-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref> Across all its ports, the game ultimately sold above 5 million units by 2006.<ref name=\"RG23\">{{cite magazine|last=Day|first=Ashley|title=The Making of... Worms|magazine=[[Retro Gamer]]|issue=23|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|date=March 2006|pages=26\u201329}}</ref>\n\n''Worms'' sharply divided critics. Reviewing the Saturn version, ''[[Sega Saturn Magazine]]'' especially praised Worms's unexpected complexity and the fun of multiplayer mode, and called it \"Quite simply the most playable game to hit the Saturn so far.\"<ref name=\"SSMukSSw\"/>\n\n''Maximum'' commented that \"Basically, ''Worms'' is ''Lemmings'', but it's without the puzzles and with weapons instead.\" While firmly stating that they found the game dull and unappealing, they acknowledged that it was clearly well-liked by gamers.<ref name=\"MaximumSSw\"/><ref name=\"MaximumSSw/>\n\nA ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' critic argued while the game resembles ''Lemmings'' on a cursory examination, in actuality it is much more similar to ''Cannon Fodder''. Praising the need for both strategy and skill, the multiplayer design, and the randomly generated landscapes, he described ''Worms'' as \"the kind of game that makes no excuses for its lack of texture-mapped polygons or its minimalist gameplay. ''Worms'' is a fun game with an infectious spirit and near endless replay value.\"<ref name=\"NGenPSw\"/><ref name=\"NGenSSw\"/>\n\nCoach Kyle of ''[[GamePro]]'' summarized that \"A humorous concept never really pays off in ''Worms''.\" He criticized that the tiny size of the characters and their weapons makes them unappealing and even hard to make out. While allowing that the use of the different weapons is interesting at first, he found the action too slow-paced and repetitive to maintain interest.<ref name=\"GProSSw\"/>\n\nThe four reviewers of ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' commented that \"Some games have great graphics and control, but ''Worms'' doesn't need either because the fun factor is a 10+. With multiplayer ability of up to four people, ''Worms'' is one of those games that is so unique, it doesn't fit into any category - except innovative and incredibly addictive.\"<ref name=\"EGMSSw\"/> They later named it one of their \"Top 5 Most Original Games of 1996\".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Top 5 Most Original Games of 1996|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=91|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=February 1997|page=152}}</ref>\n\n''[[GameSpot]]'' criticized the slowness of large multiplayer sessions and the imprecision of the keyboard controls, but, like ''Sega Saturn Magazine'', they lauded the combination of surface simplicity and underlying complexity, summarizing that \"Like the board game [[Othello (game)|Othello]], ''Worms'' takes only a few minutes to learn, but may take a lifetime to master.\"<ref name=\"GSpotPCw\"/>\n\nConversely, the ''[[Amiga Power]]'' review, written in the style of a magazine personality quiz, whilst praising the detail of the animation, described frustrating imbalances especially in relation to the vaunted 16-player multi-player mode and was critical of the puerility of the game's humour.<ref name=\"APA500w\"/>\n\n''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' named ''Worms'' a runner-up for Strategy Game of the Year (behind ''[[Dragon Force]]'').<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Best of '96|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=92|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=March 1997|page=88}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n''Worms'' is the first in the [[Worms (series)|''Worms series'']] of games.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|http://worms.team17.com/}} ''Worms'' series\n*{{MobyGames|id=/worms|name=''Worms''}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=08C-ttHHKFs Total Wormage trailer]\n\n{{Team17}}\n{{Virtual Boy}}\n{{Worms series}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|United Kingdom|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worms (1995 video game)}}\n[[Category:Worms games| 01]]\n[[Category:1995 video games]]\n[[Category:Ocean Software games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games with expansion packs]]\n[[Category:Games commercially released with DOSBox]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Artillery video games]]\n[[Category:Atari Jaguar games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Sega 32X games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Virtual Boy games]]\n[[Category:CD32 games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation (console) games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Sega Saturn games]]\n[[Category:Strategy video games]]\n[[Category:Super Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:Team17]]\n[[Category:Telegames games]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Allister Brimble]]\n", "name_user": "KGRAMR", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelease", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Worms_(1995_video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Jabal Haraz", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountain region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sana'a]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]]. In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]],<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref> and are considered part of the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sanaa, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range, a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Haraz 200612 Yemen-115 (353667843).jpg|A terraced mountain side in [[Al Mahwit Governorate]] near [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]] (the highest mountain in the [[Arabian Peninsula]])\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sanaa]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|Fortified settlement amid the mountains\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http://medomed.org/featured_item/jabal-bura-and-jabal-haraz-the-mountanous-cultural-landscape-of-yemen-yemen/ Med-O-Med: Cultural landscapes: Jabal Bura and Jabal Haraz, Yemen]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcgXBQlPUJs Jabal Haraz] ([[YouTube]])\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqJSqAjtbCA Yemen - Haraz Mountains]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbooIXhPq-E Yemen 2008 Jebel Haraz]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Yemen}}\n{{Mountains in the Arabian Peninsula}}\n\n[[Category:Jabal Haraz|*]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of mainland Yemen]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountain region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sana'a]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]]. In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]],<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref> and are considered part of the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sanaa, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range, a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Haraz 200612 Yemen-115 (353667843).jpg|A terraced mountain side in [[Al Mahwit Governorate]] near [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]] (the highest mountain in the Arabian Peninsula)\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sanaa]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|Fortified settlement amid the mountains\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http: